==L==
{{glossary}}
{{term|1= Lacunar }}
{{defn|1=Latin name in architecture for paneled or [[coffered ceiling]], [[soffit]], or [[Vault (architecture)|vault]] adorned with a pattern of recessed [[Panel painting|panel]]s.<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1 |title=Lacunar |volume=16 |page=56 |url=https://archive.org/stream/encyclopaediabri16chisrich#page/56/mode/1up}}</ref> }}

{{term|1= Latticework |content= [[Latticework]] }}
{{defn|1=An ornamental, lattice framework consisting of small strips in a criss-crossed pattern. }}

{{term|1= Light |content= [[Light (window)|Light]] }}
{{defn|1=The opening(s) in a window between mullions and muntins through which light enters an interior space.   A 6:6 window is a window that has six lights in the upper sash and six in the lower sash. }}

{{term|1= Lightning Rod |content= [[Lightning Rod]] }}
{{defn|1=A conductive bar(s) of copper or zinc coated steel mounted on the ridge or a roof or on the parapet of a building connected to a large capacity conductor, usually copper, routed to a ground rod(s) driven into the earth for the purpose of safely directing electrical charges caused by a lightning strike to the ground to avoid damage or fire to the structure. }}

{{term|1= Lintel |content= [[Lintel (architecture)|Lintel]] }}
{{defn|1=A horizontal block that spans the space between two supports usually over an opening such as a window or door. }}

{{term|1= Loculus |content= [[Loculus (architecture)|Loculus]] }}
{{defn|1=An architectural niche that houses a body, as in a catacomb, hypogeum, mausoleum or other place of entombment. }}

{{term|1= Loggia |content= [[Loggia]] }}
{{defn|1=A gallery formed by a colonnade open on one or more sides. The space is often located on an upper floor of a building overlooking an open court or garden. }}

{{term|1= Lunette |content= [[Lunette]] }}
{{defn|1=A half-moon shaped space, either masonry or void. }}
{{glossary end}}

==M==
{{glossary}}
{{term|1= Mandapa |content= [[Mandapa]] }}
{{defn|1=In [[Indian architecture]], a pillared outdoor hall or [[pavilion]] for public rituals. }}

{{term|1= Maqsurah |content= [[Maqsurah]] (maqsura) {{anchor|maqsurah|maqsura}}}}
{{defn|1=In [[Islamic architecture]], the sanctuary or praying-chamber in a mosque, sometimes enclosed with a screen of [[lattice-work]]; occasionally, a similar enclosure round a tomb. }}

{{term|1= Mansard roof |content= [[Mansard roof]] }}
{{defn|1=(French roof) A [[Hip roof|curb hip roof]] in which each face has two slopes, the lower one steeper than the upper; from the French ''mansarde'' after the accomplished 17th-century French architect noted for using (not inventing) this style, [[François Mansart]], d. 1666. }}

{{term|1= Marriage stone |content= [[Marriage stone]] }}
{{defn|1=A stone lintel, usually carved, with a marriage date. }}

{{term|1= Mascaron |content= [[Mascaron (architecture)|Mascaron]] }}
{{defn|1=A mascaron ornament is a face, usually human, sometimes frightening or chimeric, used as a decorative element. }}

{{term|1=Meander |content=[[Meander (art)|Meander]] }}
{{defn|1=Decorative border made by a repeated linear motif. }}

{{term|1= Mihrab |content= [[Mihrab]] }}
{{defn|1=In [[Islamic architecture]], a semicircular [[Niche (architecture)|niche]] in the wall of a mosque that indicates the direction of prayer. }}

{{term|1= Minaret |content= [[Minaret]] }}
{{defn|1=In [[Islamic architecture]], a tall [[spire]] with a conical or onion-shaped crown, on or near a mosque, that is used by the imam to give the prayer call. }}

{{term|1= Modillion |content= [[Modillion]] }}
{{defn|1=Enriched block or horizontal bracket generally found under the cornice and above the bedmold of the Corinthian entablature. It is probably so called because of its arrangement in regulated distances.<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1 |wstitle=Modillion}}</ref> }}

{{term|1= Molding |content= [[Molding (decorative)|Molding]] }}
{{defn|1=Decorative finishing strip. }}

{{term|1= Monotriglyph }}
{{defn|1=Interval of the [[intercolumniation]] of the [[Doric order|Doric]] column, which is observed by the intervention of one [[triglyph]] only between the triglyphs which come over the axes of the columns. This is the usual arrangement, but in the [[Propylaea]] at Athens there are two triglyphs over the central intercolumniation, in order to give increased width to the roadway, up which chariots and beasts of sacrifice ascended.<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1 |wstitle=Monotriglyph}}</ref> }}

{{term|1= Mullion |content= [[Mullion]] }}
{{defn|1=Vertical bar of wood, metal or stone which divides a window into two or more parts. }}

{{term|1=  Muqarnas|content= [[Muqarnas]]}}
{{defn|1=Type of decorative corbel used in [[Islamic architecture]] that in some circumstances, resembles stalactites. }}

{{term|1= Mutule |content= Mutule }}
{{defn|1=Rectangular block under the [[soffit]] of the cornice of the Greek Doric temple, which is studded with [[guttae]]. It is supposed to represent the piece of timber through which the wooden pegs were driven in order to hold the rafter in position, and it follows the [[cornice|sloping rake]] of the roof. In the Roman Doric order the mutule was horizontal, with sometimes a crowning fillet, so that it virtually fulfilled the purpose of the modillion in the Corinthian cornice.<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1 |wstitle=Mutule |volume=19 |page=102}}</ref> }}
{{glossary end}}

==N==
{{glossary}}
{{term|1= Narthex |content= [[Narthex]] }}
{{defn|1=An enclosed passage between the main entrance and the [[nave]] of a church. }}

{{term|1= Nave |content= [[Nave]] }}
{{defn|1=The main body of a church where the congregants are usually seated. It provides the central approach to the high [[altar]]. }}

{{term|1 = Newel|content= [[Newel]] }}
{{defn|1=The central supporting pillar of a spiral staircase. It can also refer to an upright post that supports the handrail of a stair railing and forms the lower, upper or an intermediate terminus of a stair railing usually at a landing.}}

{{term|1= Niche |content= [[Niche (architecture)|Niche]] }}
{{defn|1=In classical architecture is an [[exedra]] or an [[apse]] that has been reduced in size, retaining the half-dome heading usual for an apse. }}
{{glossary end}}

==O==
{{glossary}}
{{term|1= Oculus |content= [[Oculus]] }}
{{defn|1=A circular opening in the center of a dome such as the one in the roof of the Pantheon in Rome or in a wall. }}

{{term|1= Oillets  }}
{{defn|1=Arrow slits in the walls of medieval fortifications, but more strictly applied to the round hole or circle with which the openings terminate. The same term is applied to the small circles inserted in the tracery-head of the windows of the Decorated and Perpendicular periods, sometimes varied with trefoils and quatrefoils.<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1 |title=Oillets |volume=20 |page=43 |url=https://archive.org/stream/encyclopdiabri20chis#page/43/mode/1up}}</ref> }}

{{term|1= Onion dome |content= [[Onion dome]] }}
{{defn|1=A dome whose shape resembles an onion. }}

{{term|1= Order |content= [[Order (mouldings)|Order]] }}
{{defn|1=An order refers to each of a series of mouldings most often found in Romanesque and [[Gothic architecture|Gothic arches]]. }}

{{term|1= Orthostates |content= [[Orthostates]] }}
{{defn|1=([[Greek language|Greek]]: ὀρθοστάτης, standing upright) – Greek architecture term for the lowest course of masonry of the external walls of the [[cella|naos]] or [[cella]], consisting of vertical slabs of stone or marble equal in height to two or three of the horizontal courses which constitute the inner part of the wall.<ref>{{Cite EB1911|short=1|wstitle=Orthostatae}}</ref> }}

{{term|1= Orthostyle }}
{{defn|1=([[Greek language|Greek]]: ὃρθος, straight, and στῦλος, a column) – a range of columns placed in a straight row, as for instance those of the portico or flanks of a classic temple.<ref>{{Cite EB1911|short=1|wstitle=Orthostyle}}</ref> }}
{{glossary end}}

==P==
[[File:Screen MoorhayesChapel CullomptonChurch Devon.PNG|thumb|[[Parclose screen]], c.1530, of the [[Moor Hayes|Moorhayes]] Chapel, [[Cullompton]] Church, Devon, England]]
{{glossary}}

{{term|1= Parapet |content= [[Parapet]] }}
{{defn|1=A low wall built up above the level of a roof, to hide the roof or to provide protection against falling, and similar structures associated with balconies, bridges etc.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/english/parapet |title=Parapet defined in Oxford Dictionaries |publisher=Oxforddictionaries.com |date=1912-04-28 |accessdate=2014-05-01}}</ref> }}

{{term|1= [[Parclose screen]]}}
{{defn|1=Screen or railing used to enclose a [[chantry chapel]], tomb or [[manor|manorial chapel]], in a church, and for the space thus enclosed.<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1 |wstitle=Parclose }}</ref> }}

{{term|1= Pavilion |content= [[Pavilion]] }}
{{defn|1=A free standing structure near the main building or an ending structure on building wings. }}

{{term|1= Pedestal |content= [[Pedestal]] (also [[Plinth]]) {{anchor|pedestal|plinth}}}}
{{defn|1=The base or support on which a statue, obelisk, or column is mounted. A plinth is a lower terminus of the face trim on a door that is thicker and often wider than the trim which it augments. }}

{{term|1= Pediment |content= [[Pediment]] }}
{{defn|1=(Gr. ἀετός, Lat. ''fastigium'', Fr. ''ponton''), in classic architecture the triangular-shaped portion of the wall above the cornice which formed the termination of the roof behind it. The projecting mouldings of the cornice which surround it enclose the tympanum, which is sometimes decorated with sculpture. }}

{{term|1= Pelmet |content= [[Pelmet]] }}
{{defn|1=A framework placed above a window. }}

{{term|1= Pendentive |content= [[Pendentive]] }}
{{defn|1=Three-dimensional [[spandrels]] supporting the weight of a dome over a square or rectangular base. }}

{{term|1= Peripteral |content=[[Peripteros|Peripteral]]}}
{{defn|1=A temple or other structure surrounded on all sides by columns forming a continuous [[portico]] at the distance of one or two [[intercolumniation]]s from the walls of the [[cella|naos]] or [[cella]]. Almost all the Greek temples were peripteral, whether Doric, Ionic, or Corinthian. }}

{{anchor|Peristasis}}{{term|1= Peristasis |content=[[Peristasis (architecture)|Peristasis]]}}
{{defn|1=The Peristasis (Greek: Περίστασις) was a four-sided porch or hall of columns surrounding the [[cella]] in an ancient Greek [[peripteros]] temple (see also [[#Peristyle|Peristyle]]). In ecclesial architecture, it is also used of the area between the baluster of a Catholic church and the high altar (what is usually called the [[sanctuary]] or [[chancel]]). }}

{{anchor|Peristyle}}{{term|1= Peristyle |content=[[Peristyle]]}}
{{defn|1=a continuous porch of columns surrounding a courtyard or garden (see also [[#Peristasis|Peristasis]]). In ecclesial architecture, the term [[Glossary_of_architecture#cloister|cloister]] is used.}}

{{term|1= Phiale |content= [[Phiale (building)|Phiale]] }}
{{defn|1=A building or columned arcade around a fountain. }}

{{term|1= Piano nobile |content= [[Piano nobile]] }}
{{defn|1=The principal floor of a large house, built in the style of [[renaissance architecture]]. }}

{{term|1= Pier |content= [[Pier (architecture)|Pier]] }}
{{defn|1=An upright support for a superstructure, such as an arch or bridge. }}

{{term|1= Pilaster |content= [[Pilaster]] }}
{{defn|1=A slightly-projecting column built into or applied to the face of a wall. }}

{{term|1= Planceer |content= Planceer or Planchier {{anchor|planceer|planchier}}}}
{{defn|1=Building element sometimes used in the same sense as a [[soffit]], but more correctly applied to the soffit of the [[corona (disambiguation)|corona]] in a [[cornice]].<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1 |wstitle=Planceer |volume=5 |page=713}}</ref> }}

{{term|1= Plate Girder |content= [[Plate Girder]] }}
{{defn|1=A steel girder formed from a vertical center web of steel plate with steel angles forming the top and bottom flanges welded, bolted or riveted to the web. Some deep plate girders also may have vertical stiffeners (angles) attached to the web to resist crippling (horizontal failure) of the web.}}

{{term|1= Plinth |content= [[Plinth]] }}
{{defn|1=The base or platform upon which a column, pedestal, statue, monument or structure rests. A plinth is a lower terminus of the face trim on a door that is thicker and often wider than the trim which it augments}}

{{term|1= Poppy heads |content= [[Poppyhead (carving)|Poppyheads]]}}
{{defn|1=Finials or other ornaments which terminate the tops of bench ends, either to pews or stalls. They are sometimes small human heads, sometimes richly carved images, knots of foliage or finials, and sometimes fleurs-de-lis simply cut out of the thickness of the bench end and chamfered. The term is probably derived from the French ''poupee'' doll or puppet used also in this sense, or from the flower, from a resemblance in shape.<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1 |wstitle=Poppy Heads}}</ref> }}

{{term|1=Portcullis |content=[[Portcullis]] }}
{{defn|1=Heavy wooden or metallic grid vertically-sliding down and thus blocking the main gateway of a [[Middle Ages|medieval]] [[castle]] or fortification. }}

{{term|1= Porte-cochère |content= [[Porte-cochère]] }}
{{defn|1=A porch- or portico-like structure at a main or secondary entrance to a building through which a horse and carriage (or motor vehicle) can pass in order for the occupants to alight under cover, protected from the weather. }}

{{term|1= Portico |content= [[Portico]] }}
{{defn|1=A series of columns or arches in front of a building, generally as a covered walkway. }}

{{term|1= Prick post }}
{{defn|1=Old architectural name given sometimes to the queen posts of a roof, and sometimes to the filling in quarters in framing.<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1 |wstitle=Prick posts}}</ref> }}

{{term|1= Prostyle |content= [[Prostyle]] }}
{{defn|1=Free standing [[column]]s that are widely spaced apart in a row.  The term is often used as an [[adjective]] when referring to a [[portico]] which projects from the main structure. }}

{{term|1= Pseudodipteral |content= [[Pseudodipteral]] }}
{{defn|1=Temple similar to a [[#Dipteral|dipteral]] temple, in which the columns surrounding the naos have had walls built between them, so that they become engaged columns, as in the great temple at Agrigentum. In Roman temples, in order to increase the size of the celia, the columns on either side and at the rear became engaged columns, the portico only having isolated columns.<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1 |title=Pseudo Peripteral |volume=22 |pages=541-542 |url=https://archive.org/stream/encyclopaediabri22chisrich#page/541/mode/1up}}</ref> }}

{{term|1= Pteroma }}
{{defn|1=In Classical architecture, the enclosed space of a portico, [[#Peristyle|peristyle]], or stoa, generally behind a screen of columns. }}

{{term|1= Pycnostyle }}
{{defn|1=Term given by [[Vitruvius]] to the intercolumniation between the columns of a temple, when this was equal to one and a half diameters.<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1 |wstitle=Pycnostyle}}</ref> }}
{{glossary end}}

